You have already worked with the Gapminder world health data set in the previous block and we will revisit an updated version of it in this lab. The Gapminder foundation strives to educate people about the public health status in countries all around the world and fight devastating misconceptions that hinder world development. This information is important both for our capacity to make considerate choices as individuals, and from an industry perspective in understanding where markets are emerging. Question 1.1

rubric={reasoning:1,writing:1}

To answer the first lab question watch this 20 min video of Hans Rosling a public health professor at Karolinska Institute who founded Gapminder together with his son and his son's wife. Although the video is almost 15 years old, it is a formidable demonstration on how to present data in a way that engages your audience while conveying a strong, important message. (The original clip has over 3 million views, but I linked you one of better video quality).

Briefly describe (<=90 words) what you think is the most important message conveyed in the video and which data visualization you think was the most effective in getting this message across to the viewers.

The main message of Hans Roslings talk is that the world has improved much more than people think, and that the idea of a simple split between rich and poor countries is outdated. Most countries are moving toward better health and living standards over time. The most effective visualization is the animated bubble chart of income vs life expectancy, because seeing countries move across the plot over time makes the progress feel real, clear, and convincing rather than abstract statistics.

2. The Gapminder bubble chart

The "bubble chart" have become quite famous from their appearance in the Gapminder talks, and are widely used in other areas as well. Let's start by recreating a simple version of this chart ourselves!

There will be some data wrangling involved in this lab, and since 531 is primarily about visualization and this is the first lab, I will give you some hints for most data wrangling parts of this lab. Often I will link documentation or StackOverflow, so that you get practice finding information on these sources, and sometimes you will need to search them yourself if I haven't included a link.

To make this more interesting, I have compiled a more recent version of the Gapminder dataset, which contains values up until 2018 for most of the features. We will not use all the columns in the data set, but here is a description of what they contain that you can refer back to throughout the lab.

Column Description
country Country name
year Year of observation
population Population in the country at each year
region Continent the country belongs to
sub_region Sub-region the country belongs to
income_group Income group as specified by the world bank in 2018
life_expectancy The mean number of years a newborn would
live if mortality patterns remained constant
income GDP per capita (in USD) adjusted
for differences in purchasing power
children_per_woman Average number of children born per woman
child_mortality Deaths of children under 5 years of age per 1000 live births
pop_density Average number of people per km2
co2_per_capita CO2 emissions from fossil fuels (tonnes per capita)
years_in_school_men Mean number of years in primary, secondary,
and tertiary school for 25-36 years old men
years_in_school_women Mean number of years in primary, secondary,
and tertiary school for 25-36 years old women

3. Education balance

A common misconception is that women around the world go to school many years less than men. Lets find out what the data actually says about this.

Question 3.1

rubric={accuracy:2,quality:1,viz:2}

Python

  1. Compute a new column in your dataframe that represents the ratio between the number of years in school for women and men (calculate it so that the value 1 means as many years for both, and 0.5 means half as many for women compared to men).
  2. Filter the dataframe to only contain value from 1970 - 2015, since those are the years where the education data has been recorded. Again you can either create a new variable or perform the filtering as you pass the data to the plotting function.
  3. Create a line plot showing how the ratio of womens of mens years in school has changed over time. Group the data by income group and plot the mean for each group.
  4. Use layering to add a square mark for every data point in your line plot (so one per yearly mean in each group).
In[29]:
data['Education_Balance']=(data['years_in_school_women']/data['years_in_school_men']).round(3)
data_year=data[(data['year']>=1970) & (data['year']<=2015)]
data_for_line=data_year.groupby(['income_group','year'])['Education_Balance'].mean().reset_index()
base=alt.Chart(data_for_line).mark_line().encode(
    x='year',
    y='Education_Balance',
    color='income_group'
)
line=base.mark_line()
square=base.mark_square(size=60)
alt.layer(line,square)

In[30]:
%%R -w 550 -h 375

library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

gapminder_df <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/UofTCoders/workshops-dc-py/master/data/processed/world-data-gapminder.csv")

gapminder_df %>%
  mutate(edu_ratio_women_men = years_in_school_women / years_in_school_men) %>%
  filter(year >= 1970, year <= 2015) %>%
  group_by(income_group, year) %>%
  summarize(mean_ratio = mean(edu_ratio_women_men, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = mean_ratio, group = income_group, color = income_group)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point(shape = 15)

4. Family planning

Another common misconception is that saving the lives of children in low income countries will lead to overpopulation. Rather, lower child mortality is actually correlated with smaller family sizes. As more children survive, parents feel more secure with a smaller family size. Let's have a look in the data to see how this relationship has evolved over time.

In the plots we are going to make, it is important to note that it is not possible to tell causation, just correlation. However, in the Gapminder video library there are a few videos on this topic (including this and this one), discussing how reducing poverty can help slow down population growth through decreased family sizes. Current estimates suggest that the word population will stabilize around 11 billion people and the average number of children per woman will be close to two worldwide in year 2100.

import altair as alt
import pandas as pd

gap_df = pd.read_csv(
    "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/UofTCoders/workshops-dc-py/master/data/processed/world-data-gapminder.csv",
    parse_dates=["year"]
)

is_years = (
    (gap_df["year"] == pd.Timestamp("1918-01-01")) |
    (gap_df["year"] == pd.Timestamp("1936-01-01")) |
    (gap_df["year"] == pd.Timestamp("1958-01-01")) |
    (gap_df["year"] == pd.Timestamp("1978-01-01")) |
    (gap_df["year"] == pd.Timestamp("1998-01-01")) |
    (gap_df["year"] == pd.Timestamp("2018-01-01"))
)

gap_df = gap_df[is_years]

alt.Chart(gap_df).mark_circle(filled=True).encode(
    x = "children_per_woman",
    y = "child_mortality",
    color = "income_group",
    facet=alt.Facet(
        "year",
        columns=3
    )
)

5. Carbon dioxide emissions

CO2 emissions are often talked about in it's relation to climate change. Let's explore the data to see which countries emits the most CO2 per capita and which regions has emitted the most in total over time.

  3. Since we have only one value per country per year, lets create a bar chart to visualize it. Encode the CO2 per capita as on the x-axis, the country on the y-axis, and the region as the color.

In[49]:
import pandas as pd
import altair as alt

# Find the most recent year with 'co2_per_capita' data
most_recent_co2_year = data.dropna(subset=['co2_per_capita'])['year'].max()

# Filter data for the most recent year
co2_data_recent_year = data[data['year'] == most_recent_co2_year]
top_40_co2 = co2_data_recent_year.nlargest(40, 'co2_per_capita')

chart = alt.Chart(top_40_co2).mark_bar().encode(
    x=alt.X('co2_per_capita:Q', title='CO2 per Capita'),
    y=alt.Y('country:N', sort='-x', title='Country'),
    color=alt.Color('region:N', title='Region')
).properties(
    title=f'Top 40 Countries by CO2 per Capita in {most_recent_co2_year}'
)

In[50]:
%%R -w 500 -h 800
library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

gapminder_df <- read_csv(
  "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/UofTCoders/workshops-dc-py/master/data/processed/world-data-gapminder.csv"
)

most_recent_co2_year <- gapminder_df %>%
  filter(!is.na(co2_per_capita)) %>%
  pull(year) %>%
  max()

top_40_co2 <- gapminder_df %>%
  filter(year == most_recent_co2_year) %>%
  arrange(desc(co2_per_capita)) %>%
  slice_head(n = 40)

# Create the bar chart
ggplot(top_40_co2, aes(
    x = co2_per_capita,
    y = reorder(country, co2_per_capita),
    fill = region
  )) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(
    x = "CO2 per Capita",
    y = "Country",
    fill = "Region",
    title = paste("Top 40 Countries by CO2 per Capita in", most_recent_co2_year)
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

rubric={accuracy:1,quality:1,viz:2}

In[56]:
%%R -w 550 -h 375
library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

# Load the Gapminder data
gapminder_df <- read_csv(
  "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/UofTCoders/workshops-dc-py/master/data/processed/world-data-gapminder.csv"
)

# 1. Compute a new column 'co2_total'
gapminder_df <- gapminder_df %>%
  mutate(co2_total = co2_per_capita * population)

# Aggregate 'co2_total' by 'year' and 'region'
co2_by_region <- gapminder_df %>%
  group_by(year, region) %>%
  summarize(co2_total = sum(co2_total, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = 'drop')

# 2. Plot 'co2_total' over time in an area chart for each region
ggplot(co2_by_region, aes(
    x = year,
    y = co2_total,
    fill = region
  )) +
  geom_area(alpha = 0.3, position = 'stack') + # position='stack' to layer areas
  labs(
    x = "Year",
    y = "Total CO2 Emissions",
    fill = "Region",
    title = "Total CO2 Emissions by Region Over Time"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

import altair as alt
import pandas as pd

# 1. Wrangle data to include specific years
specific_years = [1979, 1991, 2003, 2015]
income_data_filtered = data[data['year'].isin(specific_years)]

# 2. Create a histogram of the income distribution
# 3. Facet by year and make plots smaller
chart = alt.Chart(income_data_filtered).mark_bar().encode(
    alt.X('income:Q', bin=alt.Bin(maxbins=50), title='Income (GDP per capita)'),
    alt.Y('count():Q', title='Number of Countries'),
    # Facet by year and lay out in a single row
    column=alt.Column('year:O', header=alt.Header(titleOrient="bottom", labelOrient="bottom"))
).properties(
    title='Income Distribution by Year'

7. Chart beautification

Beautifying charts can take a long time, but it is also satisfying when you end up with a really nice looking chart in the end. We will learn more about how to create charts for communication later, but these parameters are usually enough to create basic communication charts and to help you in your data exploration.

In[60]:
import pandas as pd
import altair as alt
data=pd.read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/UofTCoders/workshops-dc-py/master/data/processed/world-data-gapminder.csv")

filter_year=data['year']==1962
data_ByYear=data[filter_year]

alt.Chart(data_ByYear).mark_circle().encode(
    y = alt.Y('life_expectancy:Q', title='Life Expectancy', scale=alt.Scale(zero=False)),
    x = alt.X('children_per_woman:Q', title='Children Per Woman', scale=alt.Scale(zero=False)),
    size=alt.Size('population:Q', title='Population', scale=alt.Scale(range=[100, 1000]))
    color=alt.Color('region:N', title='Region')
).properties(
    title='Global Health Trends in 1962'
).configure_axis(
    titleFontSize=14
)

%%R -w 550 -h 375
library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

# Load 2018 Gapminder-style data directly from the URL
gapminder_df <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/UofTCoders/workshops-dc-py/master/data/processed/world-data-gapminder.csv")

# Bubble chart for a single year (1962)
gapminder_df %>%
  filter(year == "1962") %>%
  ggplot(aes(
    x = children_per_woman,
    y = life_expectancy,
    color = region,
    size = population
  )) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6) + #
  scale_size_continuous(range = c(2, 15)) +
  labs(
    title = "Global Health Trends in 1962", # Add the title
    x = "Children Per Woman", # Proper x-axis title
    y = "Life Expectancy", # Proper y-axis title
    color = "Region", # Proper color legend title
    size = "Population" # Proper size legend title
  ) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 12))
